Diagnosis . Plate generally triangular; apex narrow, digitate, directed dorsally, that protrudes for at least half its length into genital capsule; plate usually 0–3 macrosetae, sometimes one plate setous; 2.1–2.4 times as long as wide; length of apex 0.1–0.3 times as long as length of plate ( Fig. 2 c ). Style distal part separate from base; apophysis digitate, and extending about half-way into plate ( Fig. 5 ad). Female sternite 7 almost square, posterior margin ligula short, sometimes recessed into base (
Figs 7 m & n
).

Etymology
. Latin, plate, (
discus
) with apex finger-like (
digitus
).
